---
import Header from "@/components/Articles/Header.astro";
import Chapter from "@/layouts/Chapter.astro";
import Picture from "@/components/Picture.astro";
import Prose from "@/components/Articles/Prose.astro";
import Heading from "@/components/Articles/Heading.astro";
import Keyword from "@/components/Articles/Keyword.astro";
import Link from "@/components/Articles/Links/Link.astro";
---

<Chapter title="Introduction">
  <div class="px-1 md:w-3/4 lg:w-2/3 flex flex-col items-center">
    <Header
      year="2024"
      readingTime="30-38 minutes"
      codeLink="https://github.com/dyxgou/redis"
    >
      Redis: The Swiss Army Knife of Data
    </Header>

    <Picture
      class="appear w-full sm:w-3/4 aspect-square sm:aspect-video border-4"
      loading="eager"
      src="/images/redis.webp"
      alt="redis"
      size={514}
    />

    <Prose>
      <Heading id="introduction"> Introduction </Heading>

      <p>
        <strong>Redis</strong> is magical. You type <Keyword
          word="SET key value"
        />, hit enter, and in microseconds your data is stored. You type <Keyword
          word="GET key"
        />
        and it comes right back. Simple, right? But the more you <strong
          >think about it</strong
        >, the more fascinating it becomes. Somewhere between your keystrokes
        and that instant response, a <strong>server</strong> received raw bytes over
        a <strong>TCP connection</strong>, decoded them into <strong
          >meaningful commands</strong
        >, executed logic against an <strong>in-memory store</strong>, and fired
        a response back — all in the time it takes you to blink. By the end of
        this article, you won't just understand every step of that journey —
        you'll have <strong>built it yourself</strong>, in <strong
          >Golang</strong
        >, from the ground up.
      </p>

      <p>
        And the best way to understand <strong>magic</strong> is to <strong
          >learn the trick.</strong
        >
        In this article we aren't just <strong>building a clone</strong> — we are
        reverse-engineering a philosophy, diving deep into how a networked system
        actually works. We'll go from raw TCP Sockets to the implementation of RESP
        (Redis Serialization Protocol), all the way into in-memory command evaluation.
        The full source code is available on <a
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          href="https://github.com/dyxgou/redis">GitHub</a
        >! 🚀
      </p>

      <p>
        Before we dive in, here's a quick look at what <strong
          >we are going to build:</strong
        >
      </p>

      <video class="rounded-lg" width="100%" controls preload="metadata">
        <source src="/videos/redis.mp4" type="video/mp4" />
      </video>

      <h3 class="fraunces">How we will build our Clone:</h3>

      <p>
        To understand this system, we will follow a <strong>bottom-up</strong> path—starting
        with the smallest unit of data and ending with a live network interface.
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Tokens (The Vocabulary):</strong>
          A Token is the smallest atomic unit of a command. Think of them as the
          fundamental building blocks—like verbs <Keyword word="GET" /> and nouns
          <Keyword word="mykey" />.
        </li>

        <li>
          <strong>The Lexer (The Reader):</strong> If tokens are words, the <Keyword
            word="Lexer"
          /> is the "eye" that <strong>scans</strong> a sentence. It takes a raw
          string of text and groups characters together to identify the words.
        </li>

        <li>
          <strong>The Parser (The Grammar):</strong> Knowing the words <strong
            >isn't enough</strong
          >; you need to understand the sentence. The Parser acts as the
          <Keyword word="grammarian" />, organizing tokens into a structured map
          <Keyword word="AST" /> (Abstract Syntax Tree) so the computer knows exactly
          what the user is asking.
        </li>

        <li>
          <strong>The Evaluator (The Brain):</strong> Once the command is understood,
          the <Keyword word="Evaluator" /> is the <strong>decision-maker</strong
          >. It takes the parsed intent and translates it into a specific
          action.
        </li>

        <li>
          <strong>The Store (The Memory):</strong> Every system needs a place to
          keep its data. The <Keyword word="Store" /> is our <strong
            >vault</strong
          > —a thread-safe, in-memory environment where information is kept for near-instant
          retrieval.
        </li>

        <li>
          <strong>TCP Implementation (The Telephone):</strong> Finally, we’ll build
          the
          <strong>communication line</strong>. While there are many ways to
          handle networking, we’ll implement raw sockets to let the outside
          world talk to our engine.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        This article has been a labor of love over the past year, and it
        wouldn't be in its current form without the support of some incredible
        people. I want to express my deepest gratitude to my <strong
          >engineer friends</strong
        > and
        <strong>my dad</strong>: thank you for your patience in reading through
        every single iteration of this draft—your critiques were invaluable.
        Finally, a special thanks to <strong>Thorsten Ball</strong>; his book, <a
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          href="https://interpreterbook.com/">Writing An Interpreter In Go</a
        >, was the spark that inspired this entire project and provided the
        foundation for the <strong>Redis clone</strong> we are about to build.
      </p>
    </Prose>

    <Link section="requirements" />
  </div>
</Chapter>
